extremely well.

00:42:39.650 --> 00:42:40.960
They weren't expected
to do all that well.

00:42:40.960 --> 00:42:42.300
And they outperformed.

00:42:42.300 --> 00:42:44.050
And they were up against someone
whose surname was

00:42:44.050 --> 00:42:45.070
[? Pachinski. ?]

00:42:45.070 --> 00:42:47.840
And it was hard to pronounce,
a little bit hard to spell.

00:42:47.840 --> 00:42:49.930
And there was a whole argument
that part of the problem there

00:42:49.930 --> 00:42:51.580
was that when people were
saying, we should vote for

00:42:51.580 --> 00:42:52.190
[? Pachinski, ?]

00:42:52.190 --> 00:42:53.230
they didn't even know
what to say.

00:42:53.230 --> 00:42:55.050
They just said, we should vote
for that candidate who had

00:42:55.050 --> 00:42:57.500
that name that I can't remember
or pronounce.

00:42:57.500 --> 00:42:59.450
And that that stuff ends up
mattering, especially for the

00:42:59.450 --> 00:43:00.920
transmission of the name.

00:43:00.920 --> 00:43:03.755
So yes, there's been some
research on that as well.

00:43:03.755 --> 00:43:07.372
AUDIENCE: On that note, are
there any studies on people

00:43:07.372 --> 00:43:09.780
with the same name but
[INAUDIBLE] nicknames are,

00:43:09.780 --> 00:43:13.358
whether they're interpreted
differently by others or by

00:43:13.358 --> 00:43:16.830
themselves, this Kat versus
Kate versus Katie or

00:43:16.830 --> 00:43:18.330
something like that?

00:43:18.330 --> 00:43:19.920
ADAM ALTER: I don't know of
much research looking at

00:43:19.920 --> 00:43:24.780
nicknames as a distinct factor
beyond names themselves.

00:43:24.780 --> 00:43:27.480
It's an interesting question,
because obviously Kat has--

00:43:27.480 --> 00:43:28.670
or Kate or Katrina--

00:43:28.670 --> 00:43:30.720
has so many associated
nicknames.

00:43:30.720 --> 00:43:33.280
It's a good question, which
nickname should you pick?

00:43:33.280 --> 00:43:35.100
I think the main argument,
though, is nicknames are a

00:43:35.100 --> 00:43:37.980
great idea when the name is
especially complex, and you

00:43:37.980 --> 00:43:41.100
can simplify it by giving people
a nickname to use.

00:43:41.100 --> 00:43:42.880
And you see that a lot of people
with names that are

00:43:42.880 --> 00:43:45.470
hard to pronounce do this
naturally, anyway.

00:43:45.470 --> 00:43:47.500
But beyond the question of
whether one nickname is

00:43:47.500 --> 00:43:49.680
simpler than another, I don't
know about much research

00:43:49.680 --> 00:43:51.270
that's looked specifically
at nicknames.

00:43:51.270 --> 00:43:52.100
That's a good question though.

00:43:52.100 --> 00:43:52.940
Yeah.

00:43:52.940 --> 00:43:56.125
AUDIENCE: This more is for the
colors but works for anything.

00:43:56.125 --> 00:44:00.450
Have they found how much of this
is evolutionary, genetic,

00:44:00.450 --> 00:44:04.630
long-term factor versus more
social, short-term factors?

00:44:04.630 --> 00:44:05.070
ADAM ALTER: Yeah.

00:44:05.070 --> 00:44:06.800
It's a very good question.

00:44:06.800 --> 00:44:10.020
The question was, how much of
this is long-term versus

00:44:10.020 --> 00:44:13.340
evolutionary based on a very,
very long time scale?

00:44:13.340 --> 00:44:15.590
How much of it is just
based on association?

00:44:15.590 --> 00:44:17.570
That's a big question
for colors.

00:44:17.570 --> 00:44:20.540
So with drunk tank pink,
we associate pink with

00:44:20.540 --> 00:44:22.860
femininity, which we haven't
always done.

00:44:22.860 --> 00:44:25.150
So pink was a color that we
didn't associate with one

00:44:25.150 --> 00:44:28.700
gender or another until
maybe 150 years ago.

00:44:28.700 --> 00:44:30.350
And the question is, would
you have found

00:44:30.350 --> 00:44:31.670
the same effect then?

00:44:31.670 --> 00:44:33.800
There's some evidence
either way.

00:44:33.800 --> 00:44:36.650
There's one study, apparently,
that reports that even--

00:44:36.650 --> 00:44:38.600
I'm color blind, and apparently
this effect even

00:44:38.600 --> 00:44:40.230
works on color blind people.

00:44:40.230 --> 00:44:43.160
So I can't see that pink the
way you all see that pink,

00:44:43.160 --> 00:44:44.820
assuming you're not
color blind.

00:44:44.820 --> 00:44:46.800
But it's supposed to have the
same effect, which suggests

00:44:46.800 --> 00:44:49.300
something biological, at least,
beyond the level of

00:44:49.300 --> 00:44:50.870
pure association.

00:44:50.870 --> 00:44:52.800
So even if I think it's grey,
it's still doing the same

00:44:52.800 --> 00:44:53.840
thing to me.

00:44:53.840 --> 00:44:55.530
But there are other studies
that suggest that if you

00:44:55.530 --> 00:44:57.270
expect pink to make
you stronger,

00:44:57.270 --> 00:44:58.370
the effect goes away.

00:44:58.370 --> 00:45:00.000
So maybe it's about
the association.

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:02.720
If you retrain people to have
new associations, a lot of

00:45:02.720 --> 00:45:04.020
these effects go away.

00:45:04.020 --> 00:45:05.900
And it's actually a good
question, because it's a

00:45:05.900 --> 00:45:08.080
constant theme in the book
that I talk about.

00:45:08.080 --> 00:45:10.380
Some of this stuff is
very low level.

00:45:10.380 --> 00:45:13.700
It goes back well into the
reaches of the past of early

00:45:13.700 --> 00:45:16.150
humans and how they interacted
with each other.

00:45:16.150 --> 00:45:18.230
But a lot of it is really a
product of the environment we

00:45:18.230 --> 00:45:19.310
live in today.

00:45:19.310 --> 00:45:21.470
And a lot of it shows that the
environment we're in today is

00:45:21.470 --> 00:45:25.010
not the one we were over time
molded for or designed for.

00:45:25.010 --> 00:45:26.860
And so a lot of these little
errors that creep in and

00:45:26.860 --> 00:45:29.650
biases that creep in are a
product of that mismatch

00:45:29.650 --> 00:45:31.970
between the people we were
molded to be in one

00:45:31.970 --> 00:45:34.100
environment and the fact that we
haven't kept up enough with

00:45:34.100 --> 00:45:35.920
a very rapidly changing
environment.

00:45:35.920 --> 00:45:37.820
So I suggest some ways that
we might be able to

00:45:37.820 --> 00:45:41.030
cope better with that.

00:45:41.030 --> 00:45:42.926
Yeah.

00:45:42.926 --> 00:45:44.585
AUDIENCE: Is there any data
whether the pacifying effect

00:45:44.585 --> 00:45:46.244
of pink affects men
or women more?

00:45:49.170 --> 00:45:50.280
ADAM ALTER: There are
some results.

00:45:50.280 --> 00:45:52.660
And it's slightly stronger with
men than it is for women.

00:45:52.660 --> 00:45:54.890
There's one study that shows
that women don't respond as

00:45:54.890 --> 00:45:59.380
much, that in general they are
much less sensitive to the

00:45:59.380 --> 00:46:06.420
color than men are, which may
suggest, and I guess, that to

00:46:06.420 --> 00:46:08.910
some extent the effect
is about association.

00:46:08.910 --> 00:46:12.270
If men think of femininity,
perhaps that then changes how

00:46:12.270 --> 00:46:14.060
they feel when they're gripping
the hand grip,

00:46:14.060 --> 00:46:16.540
whereas women, maybe that it
just loses that effect.

00:46:16.540 --> 00:46:19.080
So perhaps it's to some extent
about the association there.

00:46:23.820 --> 00:46:25.288
Thank you.

00:46:25.288 --> 00:46:30.108
[APPLAUSE]

